<DOC><DOCNO> AP880516-0061 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-16-88 0656EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-16 0340</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0356</SECOND><HEAD>Dollar Firms</HEAD><DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The dollar firmed against most major foreigncurrencies, including the strong British pound, in quiet Europeantrading today. Gold prices also rose.   Foreign currency dealers said the dollar was supported by marketexpectations that the U.S. trade deficit narrowed in March fromFebruary's $13.8 billion. The March trade figures are scheduled tobe released in Washington on Tuesday.   Dealers said the pound continues to draw strength from anapparent dispute within the British Cabinet. One British pound cost1.8905 dollars in London at midmorning today, slightly cheaper forbuyers than late Friday's 1.8910.   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher, an advocate of free marketpolicies, opposes sustained central bank intervention to stem thepound's rise because she believes it could be inflationary. She hasstated repeatedly that controlling inflation is her primaryeconomic aim.   Her top Treasury official, Chancellor of the Exchequer NigelLawson, favors market intervention to prevent further rises in thepound which could hurt British exports and corporate profits.   In Tokyo, where trading ends as Europe's business day begins,the dollar rose 0.03 yen to a closing 124.73. Later, in London, itwas quoted at 124.78 yen.   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Friday:   --1.6857 West German marks, up from 1.6830   --1.4010 Swiss francs, up from 1.4000   --5.7205 French francs, up from 5.7063   --1.8905 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8855   --1,254.10 Italian lire, up from 1,249.00   --1.2317 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2336   Gold also firmed in moderate European trading. Bullion dealerssaid there was no market-affecting news, but there was some strongbuying from commission houses and by investors.   At midmorning, London's five major bullion dealers fixed arecommended price of $453.40 a troy ounce, up from the opening bidof $452.50 and from late Friday's 449.00.   In Zurich, the bid price was $453.50, up from $450.00 lateFriday.   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.39 to close at a bid $455.24.   Silver was quoted in London Monday at a bid $6.65 dollars a troyounce, up from Friday's $6.52.</TEXT></DOC>